subSection.paragraph:
Saponins are isolated from the crude extracts by size exclusion chromatography followed by normal phase silica gel chromatography (
Jain, 1987
; 
Wilkomirski et al., 1975
). Final purification of the compounds is done by column chromatography over normal or reverse phase silica gel (
Chen et al., 2011
; 
da Silva and Parente, 2007
; 
Eskander et al., 2010
; 
Yokosuka and Mimaki, 2007
; 
Yu et al., 2011
), droplet counter current chromatography (DCCC) in descending mode (
Jain, 1987
) and semi-preparative high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) or medium pressure liquid chromatography (MPLC) (
Perez et al., 2014
).

A classical approach for isolation of sapogenins involves acidic hydrolysis of the pulverized plant material or the crude extracts. The hydrolysate is then neutralized and extracted with organic solvents. The organic layers are then subjected to various chromatographic steps to yield pure compounds. This approach also involves conversion of saponins (glycosides) to sapogenins (aglycones) (
Blunden et al., 1980a
; 
Indrayanto et al., 1994
). However, it is possible that the hydrolysis products are not natural sapogenins but are artifacts. These artifacts may change depending upon the saponin(s), as well as the hydrolysis conditions including temperature, time and solvent used (
Olezek, 2002
). Preparative thin layer chromatography (TLC) over silica gel is also used for the isolation of sapogenins at analytical scale (
Blunden et al., 1974
).

Both spirostanol and furostanol glycosides stain yellow when the TLC is derivatized with 1% anisaldehyde and 10% sulfuric acid in methanol. While furostanol glycosides stain red with 1% dimethylaminobenzaldehyde with 10% hydrochloric acid in ethanol (Ehrlich reagent) spirostanol glycosides are colorless (
Kiyosawa et al., 1968
).

Saponins and sapogenins are separated on normal phase silica gel TLC (silver nitrate impregnation has been used in some cases) plates using a variety of mobile phases (
da Silva et al., 2002
; 
da Silva and Parente, 2005
; 
da Silva et al., 2006
; 
Ding et al., 1993
; 
Mendes et al., 2004
; 
Sharma et al., 2012
; 
Varshney et al., 1982
). Complex mixtures of sapogenins were analyzed using two-dimensional (2D) TLC over silica gel (
Blunden et al., 1974
). Conventionally, sapogenins and saponins of 

Agave

were detected using 10 
—
50% sulfuric acid followed by heating at 100 
ǫC
(
Blunden et al., 1980a
; 
Sharma et al., 2012
; 
Yi et al., 1989
), Libermann-Burchard reagent (
da Silva et al., 2006
; 
Ding et al., 1993
; 
Yu et al., 2011
), Ehrlich reagent (
Wilkomirski et al., 1975
; Yokosuka et al., 2009; 
Yokosuka and Mimaki, 2009
; 
Yu et al., 2011
), erythrocyte suspension (
Sharma et al., 2012
) and orcinol-sulfuric acid (
da Silva et al., 2002
, 
2005
; 
da Silva and Parente, 2007
), respectively.

A GLC method has been reported for determination of hecogenin (
1
) and tigogenin (
13
) in the leaves, leaf juice and sapogenin concentrates prepared from 

A. sisalana

. Prior acetylation of the sapogenins was necessary for their analyses. This method lacked specificity as the acetates of tigogenin (
13
), neotigogenin (
14
), diosgenin (
22
) and yamogenin (
23
) eluted together. Similarly, peaks for the acetates of sisalagenin (
2
) and gentrogenin (
7
) were overlapped by the hecogenin acetate (
1a
) peak (
Cripps and Blunden, 1978
). In order to increase the specificity and sensitivity of the method, hecogenin (
1
) was estimated as hecogenin 3- trifluoroacetate (
1b
) (
Matsuki et al., 1979
).

analysis) associated with GLC analysis, HPLC was evaluated for its suitability for quantitative analysis of sapogenins. A differential refractometer attached to the HPLC system allowed for detection of sapogenins without derivatization. Results of the HPLC quantification of hecogenin (
1
) and tigogenin (
2
) in the leaves of 

A. sisalana

were comparable to that obtained by GLC method (
Sitton et al., 1982
). Benzoyl esters of sapogenins of 

Agave

were also analyzed by RP-HPLC (
Higgins, 1976
). Hyphenated techniques such as HPLC coupled with mass spectrometry (HPLC-MS or LC-MS), HPLC coupled with nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy (LC-NMR) and capillary electrophoresis coupled with mass spectroscopy (CE- MS) have also been used for the rapid screening of the plant extracts/fractions for the presence of saponins (
Sarkar and Nahar, 2006
; 
Hostettmann et al., 1996
). However, examples of 

Agave

saponins analyzed by these techniques are scarce.

As is the case of sapogenins, mass spectrometry is also used to decipher the identity of sugars present in the saponins. The loss of various monosaccharide units from a saponin molecule generates the fragmentation peaks of a characteristic molecular weight. For example, the loss of a pentose moiety gives a fragment with mass [M-132] units. Similarly, loss of 146 and 162 mass units depicts cleavage of deoxyhexose (rhamnose) and hexose (glucose or galactose) moieties, respectively. 
Fig. S3
shows loss of different sugars units from the sugar portion of a) agaveside A (
111
) in the positive ion mode and b) magueyoside F (
92
) in the negative ion mode (
Pant et al., 1987
; 
Perez et al., 2014
; 
Uniyal et al., 1990
).

The 
a
, 
b
-unsaturated carbonyl (in the case of 
Δ
9(11)
) appeared at around 10 ppm upfield in comparison to the unconjugated carbonyl moiety. The position of this carbonyl group was ascertained by HMBC correlations with H 
2
-11, -14, -17 and –18 (
Perez et al., 2013
; 
Yokosuka and Mimaki, 2009
; 
Yokosuka et al., 2000
; 
Yu et al., 2011
; 
Zou et al., 2006
).

Apart from spectroscopic techniques, chemical methods are also of general applicability in structural characterization of sapogenins and saponins purified from 

Agave

. For sapogenins, chemical methods are trivially used for identification. For example, catalytic hydrogenation of yuccagenin (
24
) over Adam’ s catalyst yielded gitogenin (
15
) (
Blunden et al., 1980a
). Wolff-Kishner reduction of hecogenin (
1
) and gentrogenin (
7
) gave tigogenin (
13
) and diosgenin (
22
), respectively. Similarly, smilagenin (
17
) was formed after reduction of gloriogenin (
3
) (
Blunden et al., 1974
). Further, acetylation of sapogenins is a classic method of producing crystalline acetates having sharp melting points (
Blunden et al., 1980b
; 
Jain, 1987
; 
Sharma and Sati, 1982
).

Agave

is a suitable crop for natural and cultivated environments to withstand the stress of climate change and global warming (
Stewart, 2015
). In view of a number of bioactivities of saponins (Güçlü-Ustündağand 
Mazza, 2007
; 
Lacaille-Dubois and Wagner, 1996
; 
Lacaille-Dubois, 2005
), there is a continuing search for plants with new saponins or known saponins in higher content. With this objective, various species of the genus 

Agave

have received attention of natural products chemists.

Plant taxonomy based on morphological characteristics has inherent disadvantages (
Reynolds, 2007
; 
Ahmad et al., 2010
). Hence, there has been a need for better and more representative tools for plant identification (
Reynolds, 2007
). The presence of unique plant secondary metabolites or unique structural features of common natural plant products provides an important tool for chemotaxonomy (
Hegnauer, 1986
; 
Reynolds, 2007
). Chemotaxonomy has advantages over molecular taxonomy for systematics of 

plants (
Ernst, 2013
)

. Structural characteristics, such as the class of aglycones and the glycosylation pattern in the saponins of 

Agave

, may have a potential for use in chemotaxonomy (
Vincken et al., 2007
).
